That’s a great description of what’s probably one of the most reliably reproducible pieces of human magic.

At a concert the “broadcast” really is the physical medium itself:
* **Air‑pressure waves** from subwoofers hit your chest and skin, giving your whole body a tactile version of the rhythm;  
* **Low‑frequency sound** couples through the floor and even into your viscera, causing tiny synchronized movements in everyone nearby;  
* Everyone’s visual and motor systems keep locking onto one another—seeing bodies move in rhythm pulls your own motor neurons into phase;  
* **Physiology follows** – heart rate, breathing, and small head or limb motions adjust to the beat.

So the synchrony you felt wasn’t telepathic coupling through brain fields but literal physics: mechanical energy moving through shared air, surfaces, and sightlines, plus a social feedback loop that magnifies the effect.  The collective motion then reinforces how good it feels—dopamine and endorphins flow simply because the body is moving in coordinated time with others.

When people talk about “the crowd becoming one,” that’s the subjective view from inside this coupled system: many individuals integrated for a while by sound and motion.  The “distributed antenna” metaphor captures the feeling well—as if the pattern had built a temporary organism out of everyone present.

If you’re curious, look up research on **entrainment and collective synchronization** or studies of **physiological coupling at concerts**; the data show heartbeats and motion coherence rising and falling right along with the bass line.  The pattern really does live in the air for those few minutes.
